COG250Y1-Y-20209.courseTitle: Introduction to Cognitive Science (formerly JUP250Y1, UNI250Y1)
COG250Y1-Y-20209.courseDescription: An introduction to the problems, theories and research [strategies central to the interdisciplinary field focusing on the nature and organization of the human mind and other cognitive systems. Interrelations among the philosophical, psychological, linguistic and computer science aspects of the field are emphasized.
COG250Y1-Y-20209.deliveryInstructions: Recordings of lectures will also be available for students to view asynchronously. Tutorials will be available only as online synchronous and in person at their scheduled times.

COG260H1-F-20209.courseDescription: How does the human mind work? We explore this question by analyzing a range of data concerning such topics as human rationality and irrationality, human memory, how objects are represented in the mind, and the relation of language and cognition. This class provides critical thinking and practical computational skills that will allow students to work with data in cognitive science and related disciplines.
COG260H1-F-20209.deliveryInstructions: This is an online synchronous course. Lectures and class meetings will be live-streamed to enable real-time contact with the professor and classmates. Study materials including slides and labs will be made available online which registered students can access on their own time. Students will have the opportunity for weekly online office hours to ask questions and clarifications about course content and assignments.

LEC-0101.meetingStatusNotes: July 19, 2020: Section cancelled - course will be offered ONLSYNC only.

COG341H1-F-20209.courseTitle: Issues in Cognitive Science I: Attention, Perception, and Consciousness
COG341H1-F-20209.courseDescription: An examination of core topics in cognitive science building on introductions in COG250Y1. Typical topics include: perception and attention; concepts; imagery; consciousness.
COG341H1-F-20209.deliveryInstructions: This course will be online asynchronous, with weekly short video modules for students to view. There will also be a weekly online synchronous 1-hour discussion session in which students are strongly encouraged to participate.

COG342H1-S-20209.courseTitle: Issues in Cognitive Science II: Concepts, Theories of Mind, and Cognitive Evolution
COG342H1-S-20209.courseDescription: An examination of core topics in cognitive science building on introductions in COG250Y1. Typical topics include: concepts; theories of mind; cognitive evolution.
COG342H1-S-20209.deliveryInstructions: This course will be online asynchronous, with weekly short video modules for students to view. There will also be a weekly online synchronous 1-hour discussion session in which students are strongly encouraged to participate.

COG345H1-S-20209.courseTitle: Issues in Cognitive Science V: Cognitive Science and Society
COG345H1-S-20209.courseDescription: An examination of core topics in cognitive science building on introductions in COG250Y1. Topics include central moral, social, and political questions both relevant to and raised by cognitive science research.
COG345H1-S-20209.prerequisite: COG250Y1 and one of PSY270H1/ PHL342H1
COG345H1-S-20209.deliveryInstructions: This course will be online asynchronous, with weekly short video modules for students to view. There will also be a weekly online synchronous 1-hour discussion session in which students are strongly encouraged to participate.

COG401H1-S-20209.courseDescription: Advanced treatment of cognitive science topics for arts majors. Possible topics include: concepts, consciousness, the mind-body problem, cognitive science and the arts.
COG401H1-S-20209.deliveryInstructions: This course will be online asynchronous, with weekly short video modules for students to view. There will also be a weekly online synchronous 1-hour discussion session in which students are strongly encouraged to participate.

COG402H1-F-20209.courseDescription: Advanced treatment of cognitive science topics such as neuroscientific theories of consciousness, rationality and modelling of cognitive processes.
COG402H1-F-20209.deliveryInstructions: This is an online synchronous course. Lectures and class meetings will be live-streamed to enable real-time contact with the professor and classmates. Study materials including slides and labs will be made available online which registered students can access on their own time. Students will have the opportunity for weekly online office hours to ask questions and clarifications about course content and assignments.

COG403H1-S-20209.courseDescription: Advanced treatment of cognitive science topics, including the application of core ideas from probability theory, information theory, statistics, and machine learning to modelling human cognition and artificial intelligence.
COG403H1-S-20209.prerequisite: CSC148H1; COG250Y1; COG260H1; (MAT135H1, MAT136H1)/MAT137Y1, 0.5 FCE in statistics; 14.0 credits
COG403H1-S-20209.deliveryInstructions: This is an online synchronous course. Lectures and class meetings will be live-streamed to enable real-time contact with the professor and classmates. Study materials including slides and labs will be made available online which registered students can access on their own time. Students will have the opportunity for weekly online office hours to ask questions and clarifications about course content and assignments.

COG404H1-S-20209.courseDescription: Advanced treatment of cognitive science topics, including language processes and language representation, productions and comprehension, language acquisition, and language and theory of mind, pragmatics, reference and context.
COG404H1-S-20209.deliveryInstructions: This is an online synchronous course. Class meetings will be live-streamed to enable real-time contact with the professor and classmates. Class meetings will not be recorded, and regular live participation is required. Study materials will be made available online and students are expected to study them in their own time, prior to class meetings. Students will have the opportunity for weekly online office hours to ask questions and clarifications about course content and assignments.

COG415H1-S-20209.courseDescription: This course provides COG students with the opportunities to practice quantitative and qualitative evaluation and assessment methods in real world situations and juxtapose theory with practice. Placement activities will ground topics such as problem solving, logistics, decision making, etc., through practical application, individual and group / in-class critical reflection.
COG415H1-S-20209.deliveryInstructions: This course will be online asynchronous, with weekly recorded lectures for students to view. There will also be a weekly online synchronous 1-hour discussion session in which students are strongly encouraged to participate.
